It is bound in Rawlinson's distinctive style for binding MSS. which he specially valued, namely in red russia, with the Rawlinson heraldic mussel—shells at each corner, and the crest, a bird holding a twig in its beak, in the centre3 and Rawlinson writes at the beginning, ‘⁸ Omnium quos vidi exemplarium Bedae si artem spectes hoc est jure spectatissimum.” From West Philip Carteret Webb, whose book-plata is inserted, must have obtained it before West’s death, for the latter died in 17⁷2, and Webb in 1770, but it does not appear in the sale catalogue of his library in 1771. From him it passed to Gustavus Brander, at whose sale in 1790, Douce notes that he bought the book for only one guinea! Douce has inserted at the end a note about the Bede made by Mr. Petrie in 1828.
